28:05.517 --> 28:08.585
<i>on the road out of Deer Lake,</i>

28:08.587 --> 28:11.021
<i>the competition's still</i>
<i>riding high.</i>

28:12.290 --> 28:15.059
Well I'm glad we got the big
contract to the people.

28:15.061 --> 28:18.162
<i>Power's back on.</i>
<i>Good job, team!</i>

28:18.164 --> 28:21.031
<i>Darrell:</i>
<i>Yeah. Power's back on.</i>

28:21.033 --> 28:23.067
I really appreciate your
efforts and thank you for -

28:23.069 --> 28:24.902
Lisa: Thank you very much.
Jim: ...for making the trip.

28:24.904 --> 28:27.438
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>After making good on the most</i>
<i>important contract</i>

28:27.440 --> 28:29.973
<i>in the history</i>
<i>of their young company...</i>

28:29.975 --> 28:32.009
(Laughing) We have the power!

28:32.011 --> 28:33.744
<i>Yeah, that was a good one,</i>
<i>wasn't it?</i>

28:33.746 --> 28:35.612
Money in the bank for us, huh?

28:35.614 --> 28:38.382
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Darrell and Lisa are on their</i>
<i>way back to Winnipeg,</i>

28:38.384 --> 28:40.784
<i>stronger than ever.</i>

28:42.487 --> 28:45.489
Darrell:
Watch out for the bumps.

28:45.491 --> 28:49.927
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>And Lisa's even scored a bonus</i>
<i>back haul of scrap metal.</i>

28:49.929 --> 28:52.563
<i>Lisa:</i>
<i>One up. More than we thought</i>
<i>we were gonna get.</i>

28:57.102 --> 28:59.603
(Air hissing sound)

28:59.605 --> 29:02.172
What the (bleep) is with that?

29:03.675 --> 29:05.409
Hear it?

29:08.480 --> 29:11.982
I don't know what it is,
it's a new noise.

29:11.984 --> 29:13.150
I've got a little funny noise
in my truck,

29:13.152 --> 29:15.085
and I don't know what it is.

29:15.087 --> 29:17.154
(Warning beeps)

29:18.556 --> 29:20.023
Whoa.

29:22.494 --> 29:25.262
The truck just says I got high
coolant temp now

29:25.264 --> 29:27.931
<i>and it just shut me down.</i>

29:28.933 --> 29:30.601
(Warning beeps)

29:32.003 --> 29:33.237
Having some problems here.

29:33.239 --> 29:35.439
<i>I don't know what's going</i>
<i>on for sure.</i>

29:35.441 --> 29:38.308
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>But as they near the end</i>
<i>of the winter road...</i>

29:38.310 --> 29:40.711
Are you pulling right over or
just stopping right here or...?

29:40.713 --> 29:43.847
<i>Darrell:</i>
<i>Well, I don't have much of a</i>
<i>place to pull over here.</i>

29:43.849 --> 29:45.582
(Airbrakes hiss)

29:52.257 --> 29:54.324
What a pain in the ass.

30:00.665 --> 30:03.467
<i>What the hell?</i>

30:03.469 --> 30:06.470
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>The diagnosis?</i>
<i>A busted fan belt.</i>

30:06.472 --> 30:08.338
<i>Darrell:</i>
<i>Supposed to turn around</i>
<i>and round,</i>

30:08.340 --> 30:10.140
<i>and it went to (bleep).</i>

30:10.142 --> 30:13.911
And so when it went to (bleep),
it ate my fan belt.

30:13.913 --> 30:17.948
There's no water circulating,
you know.

30:17.950 --> 30:19.716
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>And with the engine</i>
<i>overheating,</i>

30:19.718 --> 30:24.488
<i>getting the rig home over the</i>
<i>last 100 miles is a long shot.</i>

30:24.490 --> 30:27.057
I know I can't leave it sitting
out here on the road.

30:27.059 --> 30:29.626
So we might have to call
a tow truck then, huh?

30:29.628 --> 30:31.929
<i>Darrell:</i>
<i>Another tow truck.</i>

30:31.931 --> 30:34.731
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>But for a small company without</i>
<i>an infrastructure,</i>

30:34.733 --> 30:38.602
<i>getting towed this far</i>
<i>would cost a fortune.</i>

30:38.604 --> 30:40.704
<i>Darrell:</i>
<i>Huh. Ain't nothin' I can</i>
<i>do about it.</i>

30:40.706 --> 30:42.639
<i>I don't have the parts</i>
<i>to fix it.</i>

30:47.879 --> 30:51.114
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>On the road home</i>
<i>from Deer Lake...</i>

30:51.116 --> 30:53.350
There's no water circulating.

30:53.352 --> 30:57.554
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>A busted fan belt has</i>
<i>Darrell's engine overheating.</i>

30:57.556 --> 30:58.622
Ain't nothin' I can do
about it.

30:58.624 --> 31:00.858
I don't have the parts
to fix it.

31:00.860 --> 31:02.459
<i>I don't have a idler pulley.</i>

31:02.461 --> 31:04.962
<i>Lisa:</i>
<i>I guess try to get it up</i>
<i>to some place.</i>

31:04.964 --> 31:06.663
<i>Darrell:</i>
<i>Some place off the road,</i>
<i>anyway.</i>

31:10.802 --> 31:13.303
<i>Lisa:</i>
<i>I'm good.</i>

31:13.305 --> 31:16.874
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Darrell will attempt to limp</i>
<i>to the nearest pullout,</i>

31:16.876 --> 31:19.977
<i>and the team will have</i>
<i>to absorb a massive tow bill</i>

31:19.979 --> 31:21.745
<i>to the closest mechanic,</i>

31:21.747 --> 31:25.616
<i>wiping away a hefty chunk</i>
<i>of their new profits.</i>

31:27.485 --> 31:30.954
The idler pulley broke,
and so the fan belt shredded,

31:30.956 --> 31:33.824
and now he can't cool
his truck,

31:33.826 --> 31:37.895
so he can only drive until
it gets hot.

31:37.897 --> 31:39.496
<i>Yeah, the engine's gotta cool</i>

31:39.498 --> 31:42.566
or it's going to overheat
and seize.

31:44.002 --> 31:46.203
How's your temperature holding?

31:46.205 --> 31:47.638
Yeah it's right touching red.

31:47.640 --> 31:50.674
The light hasn't come on yet,
but it's going to.

31:50.676 --> 31:53.010
I'm in neutral rolling.

31:53.012 --> 31:57.614
Lisa:
As soon as it hits the red,
it's going to shut down.

31:58.783 --> 32:00.484
I gotta find a place
to get it off the road,

32:00.486 --> 32:05.455
some place where I can get it
worked on or get a tow truck.

32:06.791 --> 32:08.358
(Warning beeps)

32:08.360 --> 32:10.494
There it goes.

32:12.397 --> 32:14.164
I have no power,
I have no throttle,

32:14.166 --> 32:15.799
I'm in neutral,
the engine is running,

32:15.801 --> 32:17.601
but it's at an idle.

32:17.603 --> 32:19.469
<i>Lisa! My truck just died.</i>

32:21.306 --> 32:23.473
She ain't going to make it home
at this rate.

32:29.480 --> 32:31.715
Yeah, I'd love to push ya.

32:33.051 --> 32:35.519
Keep coming and push.

32:41.092 --> 32:45.562
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Push trucking is a way for two</i>
<i>trucks to use the power of one</i>

32:45.564 --> 32:47.531
<i>by using the power of the</i>
<i>bumper of the truck in back</i>

32:47.533 --> 32:50.634
<i>to push the dead one up front.</i>

32:50.636 --> 32:52.402
<i>But it's a dangerous manoeuvre</i>

32:52.404 --> 32:55.906
<i>as the rear truck must lock</i>
<i>with its convoy partner,</i>

32:55.908 --> 32:59.142
<i>and the truck up front must</i>
<i>steer for both of them.</i>

33:02.981 --> 33:04.648
Lisa:
I need a nice smooth landing,

33:04.650 --> 33:07.150
which involves me using my
brake and my throttle

33:07.152 --> 33:09.152
at the same time.

33:09.154 --> 33:10.854
<i>It's like this moving target.</i>

33:10.856 --> 33:12.622
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>It ain't for rookies.</i>

33:12.624 --> 33:15.392
<i>It takes a seasoned hand,</i>
<i>and most of all,</i>

33:15.394 --> 33:17.894
trust between the two partners.

33:17.896 --> 33:20.530
Don't hit him hard!

33:20.532 --> 33:21.999
<i>Oh my god!</i>

33:22.001 --> 33:24.368
I can't even see the back
of this trailer at all,

33:24.370 --> 33:27.204
like there I can see
the taillights.

33:27.206 --> 33:28.939
(Loud clang)

33:30.341 --> 33:33.010
Oof! That was harder
than I wanted.

33:33.012 --> 33:35.178
<i>Darrell:</i>
<i>That's all right,</i>
<i>it wasn't bad.</i>

33:41.986 --> 33:43.653
I think I came off of here.

33:43.655 --> 33:47.758
Yeah, I think you did. I'm
on the brakes a little bit.

33:47.760 --> 33:51.762
<i>Lisa:</i>
<i>All right, I'll come back up</i>
<i>to ya.</i>

33:54.132 --> 33:55.932
(Loud clang)
Darrell: Whoa!

33:55.934 --> 33:57.667
I knew that was too hard.

33:57.669 --> 34:01.304
Good thing we got that bumper
put on your truck, Lisa.

34:01.306 --> 34:03.140
(Loud clang)

34:03.142 --> 34:05.008
<i>Darrell:</i>
<i>Hammer down, hammer down.</i>

34:05.010 --> 34:07.144
<i>Lisa:</i>
<i>So I'm trying to be smooth</i>

34:07.146 --> 34:10.280
<i>I don't want to bend</i>
<i>the bars of my radiator.</i>

34:10.282 --> 34:12.349
(Loud clang)

34:14.385 --> 34:17.954
<i>Darrell:</i>
<i>Keep it tight. Hammer down!</i>

34:19.357 --> 34:23.193
Lisa's on my ass pushing, and
we're going down the highway.

34:23.195 --> 34:25.062
Lisa:
So I'm kind of fighting
with the steering wheel,

34:25.064 --> 34:27.297
I don't know why.

34:27.299 --> 34:29.132
You don't need to steer.

34:29.134 --> 34:30.467
<i>As long as I'm connected</i>
<i>to Darrell,</i>

34:30.469 --> 34:33.236
he's telling my tires
where to go.

34:33.238 --> 34:38.075
So I have to trust that he is
gonna steer me in good places,

34:38.077 --> 34:41.144
<i>and not got too fast</i>
<i>around corners.</i>

34:42.313 --> 34:44.281
And that he's not gonna
put me in another lane,

34:44.283 --> 34:46.483
he's not going to put me
in a snow bank.

34:46.485 --> 34:49.019
<i>Darrell:</i>
<i>I don't know how far we're</i>
<i>gonna have to go like this.</i>

34:49.021 --> 34:51.421
<i>I guess we'll see</i>
<i>what we've got.</i>

34:51.423 --> 34:54.491
<i>Lisa:</i>
<i>We're doing fine, so we may as</i>
<i>well just roll with it for now.</i>

34:57.095 --> 34:58.995
(Chuckles)

35:00.164 --> 35:01.698
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>For the next 70 miles,</i>

35:01.700 --> 35:04.835
<i>the team skilfully pushes</i>
<i>their way down the road.</i>

35:07.505 --> 35:09.172
<i>Until finally...</i>

35:10.274 --> 35:13.310
<i>Lisa:</i>
<i>Now we're just pulling</i>
<i>into this truck stop.</i>

35:13.312 --> 35:15.078
We're off the road and
we're in a pullout now.

35:15.080 --> 35:18.415
That was a crazy long ways
to go and find a pullout.

35:18.417 --> 35:20.317
The next town.

35:20.319 --> 35:22.018
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>They arrive at a service</i>
<i>station,</i>

35:22.020 --> 35:25.155
<i>and they're able to avoid</i>
<i>a huge financial hit.</i>

35:26.524 --> 35:28.158
<i>So by the time we were done,</i>

35:28.160 --> 35:30.694
<i>Lisa pushed me</i>
<i>for 120 kilometres</i>

35:30.696 --> 35:32.195
<i>to get me back</i>
<i>to the nearest town</i>

35:32.197 --> 35:34.831
where I could get some repair
work done on my truck.

35:34.833 --> 35:37.300
You know, when you're locked
to the back of me like that,

35:37.302 --> 35:39.369
you're pretty much
at the mercy of me driving.

35:39.371 --> 35:40.770
Yeah, I trust you.

35:40.772 --> 35:42.572
(Laughing) I wouldn't
have wanted anybody else

35:42.574 --> 35:46.109
pushing me 120 kilometres
at 80 kilometres an hour.

35:46.111 --> 35:47.677
(Laughing)

35:50.481 --> 35:53.016
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>As night falls...</i>

35:53.018 --> 35:54.951
<i>Todd:</i>
<i>You know, it's about 11:00</i>
<i>at night.</i>

35:54.953 --> 35:57.521
I'm just about to Tadoule Lake,
<i>now.</i>

35:57.523 --> 36:00.590
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Todd Dewey's closing in</i>
<i>on his final offload,</i>

36:00.592 --> 36:03.426
<i>trying hard to make up</i>
<i>for a key mistake.</i>

36:03.428 --> 36:04.828
I'm gonna be honest,

36:04.830 --> 36:08.999
I am beat to the core after
what I had to do today.

36:09.001 --> 36:11.234
<i>This is like a two</i>
<i>to three day run,</i>

36:11.236 --> 36:12.769
<i>and I'm basically doing it</i>
<i>in about one day,</i>

36:12.771 --> 36:15.005
<i>in about 18 or 19 hours</i>
<i>straight,</i>

36:15.007 --> 36:19.176
<i>just pushing as hard as I can</i>
<i>to get these loads delivered.</i>

36:19.178 --> 36:22.746
<i>I can't get dumped until</i>
<i>you know, in the morning.</i>

36:22.748 --> 36:24.814
I'm tired, I'm worn out.

36:26.951 --> 36:28.552
<i>So, I'm going to pull</i>
<i>over here,</i>

36:28.554 --> 36:32.822
<i>and just have myself</i>
<i>a warm can of soup.</i>

36:32.824 --> 36:34.357
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>The life of an ice road trucker</i>

36:34.359 --> 36:36.993
<i>means eating and sleeping</i>
<i>on the trail.</i>

36:36.995 --> 36:38.195
Okay.

36:38.197 --> 36:39.262
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>And tonight...</i>

36:39.264 --> 36:41.531
Todd:
I'm just going to grab
this log.

36:41.533 --> 36:44.801
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>It's dinner on the roadside.</i>

36:44.803 --> 36:48.104
(Grunts) Good old firewood
laying in the bush,

36:48.106 --> 36:50.273
nice and dry.

36:50.275 --> 36:53.176
Get ourselves a little
fire going.

36:53.178 --> 36:55.178
(Pouring lighter fluid)

36:56.414 --> 36:58.315
Watch out.

36:59.584 --> 37:01.318
Come on, baby, get goin'!

37:01.320 --> 37:03.220
(Fire crackles)
Ha ha!

37:04.488 --> 37:06.556
(Flames whoosh)

37:07.725 --> 37:09.392
Oh, that feels good, baby.

37:09.394 --> 37:11.428
That's what I'm talkin' about.

37:11.430 --> 37:14.130
Set a little can of stew
on there.

37:15.099 --> 37:17.500
Be eatin' good tonight.

37:17.502 --> 37:24.374
<i>enjoy a little hot fire</i>
<i>and kind of warm up my soul</i>
<i>a little bit.</i>

37:24.376 --> 37:25.875
<i>Enjoy a little bit</i>
<i>of what God gave us</i>

37:25.877 --> 37:27.344
<i>down here to enjoy on earth,</i>

37:27.346 --> 37:29.813
and why not make a few memories
up here

37:29.815 --> 37:32.115
while a guy is working
his ass off, you know.

37:32.117 --> 37:35.285
<i>Couldn't ask for a better way</i>
<i>to end a long day on the ice</i>
<i>roads.</i>

37:40.992 --> 37:44.327
<i>As dawn breaks</i>
<i>on the ice roads...:</i>

37:44.329 --> 37:46.563
<i>Todd:</i>
<i>Well, we're up and rolling</i>
<i>this morning.</i>

37:46.565 --> 37:48.965
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Todd Dewey's made it</i>
<i>to his destination.</i>

37:49.967 --> 37:53.637
That's the town, the big town
of Tadoule Lake.

37:53.639 --> 37:58.141
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>And the missing blades,</i>
<i>and load of lumber,</i>

37:58.143 --> 38:00.043
<i>are safely delivered.</i>

38:00.045 --> 38:02.646
<i>Todd:</i>
<i>You know what, I got down</i>
<i>the road, fought hard,</i>

38:02.648 --> 38:06.716
got to the airport, got the
grader blades delivered.

38:08.352 --> 38:11.588
<i>Mark was happy, I was happy,</i>
<i>the airport was happy,</i>

38:11.590 --> 38:13.990
<i>my mission was accomplished,</i>
<i>and I was good.</i>

38:13.992 --> 38:17.027
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>With the government contract</i>
<i>fulfilled for Polar...</i>

38:17.029 --> 38:19.396
Todd:
That's it! That's a wrap!

38:19.398 --> 38:23.366
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>The company top dog may be</i>
<i>out of the doghouse for good.</i>

38:23.368 --> 38:24.834
Todd:
Woo!

38:29.907 --> 38:33.543
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>400 miles to the southeast,</i>

38:33.545 --> 38:35.412
<i>in the rapidly melting Tundra,</i>

38:35.414 --> 38:37.380
(Bleep)

38:37.382 --> 38:39.949
<i>a Polar team-mate's</i>
<i>trying to get home.</i>

38:39.951 --> 38:42.285
<i>Art:</i>
<i>Grey out here. Everything</i>
<i>is all melted to hell,</i>

38:42.287 --> 38:43.753
<i>it's all mud.</i>

38:43.755 --> 38:46.289
The road is rough.
It's a bastard.

38:46.291 --> 38:48.425
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Art Burke's taken an</i>
<i>alternative route</i>

38:48.427 --> 38:51.895
<i>out of distant Sachigo Lake.</i>

38:51.897 --> 38:52.996
We get this (bleep)
and over with

38:52.998 --> 38:55.298
make our way to (bleep)
Winnipeg, b'y.

38:55.300 --> 39:02.405
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Looking for a trial that</i>
<i>hasn't been destroyed</i>
<i>by the warming weather.</i>

39:02.407 --> 39:04.641
The weather's getting
pretty warm, b'y.

39:08.079 --> 39:11.314
When things are going well,
this is a fantastic job,

39:11.316 --> 39:15.051
<i>but when it's not,</i>
<i>it's a (bleep) terrible job.</i>

39:17.588 --> 39:19.389
<i>Okay, now what?</i>

39:20.891 --> 39:23.126
Now what?

39:23.128 --> 39:25.795
Well, I don't know.

39:27.631 --> 39:29.399
We're at a V in the road here.

39:29.401 --> 39:31.468
I'm not real positive,

39:31.470 --> 39:35.805
but I'm pretty (bleep) sure
we go this way.

39:37.908 --> 39:39.909
So this is the way we're going.

39:43.013 --> 39:45.515
I hope (bleep) I made the right
<i>decision here.</i>

39:45.517 --> 39:48.251
<i>I got a 50 percent chance</i>
<i>of getting this right.</i>

39:48.253 --> 39:49.352
Out here in the middle
of nowhere,

39:49.354 --> 39:51.988
like there is these roads
going everywheres, eh.

39:51.990 --> 39:53.189
<i>You gotta be awful careful</i>

39:53.191 --> 39:54.791
<i>because there's so many</i>
<i>of them,</i>

39:54.793 --> 39:58.361
<i>that it's hard to keep track,</i>
<i>eh?</i>

39:58.363 --> 40:00.530
But I'm pretty sure that this
is the right way to go here.

40:00.532 --> 40:02.766
This is the way I'm going.

40:04.034 --> 40:07.137
And if I arss'd up,
Well, it's too late now,

40:07.139 --> 40:08.338
I gotta go right to the end
of this

40:08.340 --> 40:10.974
because there's no place
to turn around, b'y.

40:10.976 --> 40:14.277
Off we go,
down the bouncy ice road.

40:14.279 --> 40:17.046
(Laughs)
And hope for the best!

40:21.452 --> 40:25.855
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>But the path has a surprise</i>
<i>for him.</i>

40:27.091 --> 40:31.694
<i>An unmarked ice crossing</i>
<i>that's getting cooked...</i>

40:31.696 --> 40:34.197
<i>under the hot sun.</i>

40:34.199 --> 40:36.699
<i>Art:</i>
<i>I mean it's gotta be</i>
<i>the right (bleep) way.</i>

40:36.701 --> 40:40.503
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>And it looks more like a river</i>
<i>than a road.</i>

40:40.505 --> 40:42.906
They wouldn't make an ice road
like this for nothin'.

40:45.943 --> 40:48.144
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>At a wheel and a prayer...</i>

40:48.146 --> 40:49.779
(Shifting gears)

40:49.781 --> 40:50.413
